      "I called.\n\nI almost didn't, which is the part I need to write down before I let myself feel good about it.\n\nIt was Wednesday evening. Sam was out — some work thing that ran late — and I was doing that thing where I move around the apartment without actually doing anything. Opened the fridge. Closed it. Picked up a book, read the same paragraph twice. Opened my phone and started scrolling in a way that had no destination.\n\nAnd then I just dialed. Not because I'd built up to it or given myself a pep talk. More like I caught myself mid-drift and did it before the voice that would have talked me out of it could find its footing.\n\nRiley picked up on the second ring.\n\n\"I was starting to think you'd moved,\" Riley said. Not mean — Riley doesn't do mean — but honest. The kind of joke that has some real weight in it.\n\nI said, \"I know. I'm sorry. I've been bad at this.\"\n\nAnd Riley said, \"Yeah.\" Just that. Just — yeah.\n\nWe were on the phone for almost two hours. I don't know what I'd been so afraid of exactly, or maybe I do and it just turned out not to be true. We sounded like ourselves. Old selves and current selves, both at once. Riley has been going through something with a job situation that's complicated in ways I won't try to compress here, and I talked about the Mei thing — the deck, the verdict feeling, some of it — and Riley asked good questions the way Riley always did, the way that makes you feel like your half-formed thing is worth examining.\n\nAt some point Riley said, \"You know what's funny, I always assumed you had everything more figured out than me.\" And I didn't know what to do with that so I laughed, and Riley laughed, and we moved on. But it's been sitting with me since. The idea that I've been carrying around this low-grade envy of people who seem more settled, more confident, more whatever — Devon going quiet at work, someone from college posting about a promotion — and meanwhile Riley was apparently on the other side of the same glass thinking something similar about me. Everyone looking slightly sideways at someone else's life.\n\nI don't know what to do with that information either. But it was good to hear.\n\nThe forty-three second voicemail, by the way — I finally listened to it before I called. It was literally just Riley saying, \"Hey, haven't heard from you in a while, wondering how you're doing, no rush, call me when you can.\" That's it. Forty-three seconds of warmth and zero emergency. I had been protecting myself from that for a month.\n\n\"No rush, call me when you can.\" I had turned that into something complicated enough to avoid for four weeks.\n\nWhen Sam got home I was still on the couch, phone on my chest, sort of staring at the ceiling in a not-bad way. Sam asked how my night was and I said, \"I finally called Riley.\" And Sam's face did something — not a big expression, just a small settling, like a thing that had been gently worrying Sam had been resolved. I hadn't realized Sam was holding that too. I hadn't realized how visible my avoidance is, even when I think I'm being private about it.\n\nWe made tea and I told Sam some of what Riley and I talked about. The job thing, the way it felt to just be back in that frequency with someone. Sam listened without saying much, which is the kind of listening I needed.\n\nThis morning I took a longer walk. I didn't plan to — I just kept going past the usual turn. It was still early enough that the city was mostly people with dogs and other people who look like they're solving something in their heads while they move. I thought about Riley, and I thought about how much energy I spent not doing the thing versus just doing the thing. The call took two hours. The not-calling took a month of small mental overhead, the voicemail length memorized, the Wednesday dishes confrontation with myself, the phone pulled out on the walk and put away again.\n\nI'm not going to say I've learned something and now I'll be different. I know myself well enough to know there's probably another call I'm already not making to someone, another thing at eighty percent I've told myself is done. The pattern doesn't break because you see it one time clearly.\n\nBut I called Riley. And it was the forty-three seconds I knew it would be, expanded into two hours of just — talking to a person I actually miss. That's all it was. That's all it ever would have been.",
