    content:
      "I told her.\n\nIt was Thursday, which means I let Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday go by first. So the honest version starts there.\n\nMonday I had a reason — she was in back-to-back meetings and I didn't want to catch her in a hallway, didn't want it to feel like an ambush, told myself I'd find a better moment. Tuesday the better moment existed and I walked past it. We were in a small working session, just the two of us and Devon, and Devon stepped out to take a call, and there were maybe four minutes where it was just Mei and me and the room. I could feel the four minutes. I watched them happen. Mei was typing something and I said, \"I think the timeline on this is going to be tighter than it looks,\" which is a true sentence about a project and also the most spectacular waste of four minutes I've managed recently.\n\nWednesday I drafted the email again. Third draft, which was better than the first two — more direct, less over-explained, no paragraph where I preemptively listed my qualifications as if I were filing an application. I got it to a place where I thought, okay, this is actually just a normal thing a person would send. And then I did not send it.\n\nWhat I did instead on Wednesday night: watched something on my phone until eleven, thought about the project lead thing in the vague circular way that produces nothing, and fell asleep telling myself that Thursday was actually the better day anyway because Mei tends to be more available in the afternoons.\n\nWhich was maybe even true. But I knew what I was doing.\n\nThursday afternoon she was at her desk and not on a call and I walked over with no document in my hands this time. Nothing to deliver. Just walked over. My heart was doing the thing it does when your body knows you're about to make yourself a little vulnerable and would like you to reconsider.\n\nI said, \"Hey — I want to be direct about something. The new project you mentioned a few weeks ago, needing a lead. I'd like to be considered for it.\"\n\nThat's it. That's all I'd been storing behind a month of email drafts and walked-past moments and Wednesday nights on the couch.\n\nMei looked up and there was a beat — not the pause I'd been dreading, the one that means she's searching for a kind way to say she hadn't been thinking of me. More like she was shifting gears. \"I was hoping you'd bring that up,\" she said. \"I wasn't sure if you wanted it.\"\n\nI didn't know what to do with that so I just said, \"I want it.\"\n\nShe said she hadn't made any decisions and there were a couple of things she wanted to think through, but that she was glad I said something. She said it exactly like that — glad I said something — and there was no performance in it. She meant it.\n\nAnd then it was over. The whole thing was maybe ninety seconds.\n\nI walked back to my desk and sat there for a minute just breathing. Not the stunned, complicated stare-at-the-ceiling thing from after the Riley call. Just — quieter. Like a hum I'd gotten used to had stopped and now the room sounded different.\n\nI texted Sam: \"talked to Mei about the lead thing.\" Sam wrote back a string of nothing but punctuation that I understood completely.\n\nHere's the thing I keep turning over: she was hoping I'd bring it up. Which means she'd been waiting. Which means there was a version of the last few weeks where she was wondering if I wanted it, and I was too busy not-walking-into-the-room to answer the question she was already holding. We were on opposite sides of the same silence.\n\n\"You don't ask for things.\" That's what the harsh voice had been saying. And it wasn't wrong, exactly — I do have a pattern there, the conference Devon went to, the deck I let sit at eighty percent, the whole infrastructure I've built for wanting things quietly from a distance. But the voice said it like a permanent fact, like a door that had been locked from the outside. And Thursday it was just a door. I knocked and it opened.\n\nI don't know yet what Mei decides. She might go with Devon. She might go with someone else entirely. I can't control that part, which was the thing my brain kept using as a reason not to try — if the outcome is uncertain, don't expose the wanting. Keep it safe in the draft folder.\n\nBut I said the words. In the actual room. With my actual voice. And she was glad I did.\n\nThis morning's walk was good. Not longer than usual, not shorter. I passed the corner where the dry cleaner used to be — I always pass that corner — and I thought about the deck and Riley and now this, this particular week, and how the thing in the waiting room has a way of getting heavier the longer it sits there. Not because it grows. Just because you keep paying a little attention to it every day and that adds up, and at some point you're maintaining the weight of it full-time.\n\nI'd like to try to do the next one faster. Maybe that's the only thing I'm actually learning. Not how to stop being afraid of the door. Just how to shorten the hallway.",
